description: Attested since the 17th century, from Latin impāctus, perfect passive participle of impingō (“dash against, impinge”), from in- + pangō (“fasten, drive in”), ultimately from Proto-Indo-European *peh₂ǵ-.

entries.meaning: The striking of one body against another; collision.
The force or energy of a collision of two objects.
(figurative, proscribed) A significant or strong influence or effect.
The striking of one body against another; collision.
The force or energy of a collision of two objects.
examples: The hatchet cut the wood on impact.
His spine had an impingement; L4 and L5 made impact, which caused numbness in his leg.

entries.meaning: (figurative, proscribed) A significant or strong influence or effect.
examples: His friend's opinion had an impact on his decision.
Our choice of concrete will have a tremendous impact on the building's mechanical performance.

verbs.description: impact (third-person singular simple present impacts, present participle impacting, simple past and past participle impacted)

entries.meaning: (transitive) To collide or strike, the act of impinging.
examples: When the hammer impacts the nail, it bends.

entries.meaning: (transitive) To compress; to compact; to press into something or pack together.
examples: The footprints of birds do not impact the soil in the way those of dinosaurs do.

entries.meaning: (transitive, figurative, proscribed) To significantly or strongly influence or affect; to have an impact on.
examples: I can make the changes, but it will impact the schedule.

entries.meaning: (transitive, rare) To stamp or impress onto something.
